\b \cf0 Software needed to work with ESP-r
\b0 \
\
\pard\tx566\tx1133\tx1700\tx2267\tx2834\tx3401\tx3968\tx4535\tx5102\tx5669\tx6236\tx6803\pardirnatural

\fs20 \cf0 The base install of Ubuntu has much of what you need. The installation of new software packages and their dependencies is handled via package managers (command line apt-get) or a graphic package manager such as Synaptic (found in System -> Administration). In the search dialog type in some or all of the package name you are looking for and a list of possible choices will be displayed.  For example, to install the helper tool xfig the syntax would be:\
\
\pard\tx566\tx1133\tx1700\tx2267\tx2834\tx3401\tx3968\tx4535\tx5102\tx5669\tx6236\tx6803\pardirnatural

\b \cf0   apt-get install xfig\
\pard\tx566\tx1133\tx1700\tx2267\tx2834\tx3401\tx3968\tx4535\tx5102\tx5669\tx6236\tx6803\pardirnatural

\b0 \cf0 \
which will also list and install dependencies needed for the software to run.  \
\
Lets begin with the minimal requirements to run either the X11 or GTK version of ESP-r.\
\
ESP-r requires libgfortran, ImageMagick, xfig (for vector graphics export) and a text editor such as nedit.  Once these are in place you should be able to use the standard self-extracting installer for ESP-r on Linux.\

